age, and (2) link your document to this URL in a web document or cite the <span class="website">Victorian Web</span> in a print one.]</p><a href="../../../misc/usp.html"><img src="../../../icons2/usp2.gif" border="0" height="120"/></a></div></div><div id="footer"><h3>Commentary: The Community Celebrates the Marriage of Meg and Richard</h3> <p class="one">Neither <span class="book">The Chimes: A Goblin Story of Some Bells ThatRang An Old Year Out and a New Year In</span> (1844) nor either of the <a href="../barnard/household.html">Household Edition</a> volumes from Chapman and Hall (illustrated by <a href="../barnard/index.html">Fred Barnard</a>) and Harper and Brothers (illustrated by <a href="../abbey/index.html">E. A. Abbey</a>) has an illustration of just Trotty and Mrs. Chickenstalker dancing. The groceresss would seem to be a sort of honorary "Mother of the Bride" in Leech's final&eacute;, as the original volume features her prominently in this full-page wood-engraving dropped into the letterpress of the thirteenth and final scene, involving the musicians (rear) and Meg and Richard, as well as numerous other "country" dancers.</p><h3>Illustrations from the Pears' Centenary Edition (1912) and the Charles Dickens Library Edition (1910)</h3> <center><a href="../green/42.html"><img src="../green/42.jpg" height="420" hspace="5" border="0"/></a><a href="../furniss/68.html"><img src="../furniss/68.jpg" height="420" hspace="5" border="0"/></a></center> <p class="tc">Left: Charles Green's <span class="tcartwork">The Dance on the Eve of Meg's Wedding Day</span> (1912?). Right: Harry Furniss's study of Trotty'sseeing his daughter, her fianc&eacute;, Lilian, and Mrs. Chickenstalker happily dancing in his dream, from which he appears to be awakening, <span class="tcartwork">Trotty's Dream</span>, the culminating illustration in Furniss's 1910 series.</p><h3>Related Materials and Details</h3><ul>	<li><a href="../../../authors/dickens/xmas/index.html"><span class="book">The 	Christmas Books</span> of Charles Dickens</a></li>	<li>Sol Eytinge, Jr.'s single illustration for <a href="../eytinge/161.html"><span 	class="book">The Chimes</a> (1867)</li>	<li>A. E. Abbey's Household Edition illustrations for 	<a href="../abbey/index.html"><span class="book">The Christmas Books</a> (1876)</li>	<li>Fred Barnard's Household Edition illustrations for 	<a href="../barnard/xmas/index.html"><span class="book">The Christmas Books</a> (1878)</li>	<li>Harry Furniss's illustrations for Dickens's 	<a href="../furniss/xmas.html"><span class="book">The Chimes</span></a> (1910)</li>	<li>Charles Green's illustrations for Dickens's <a href="../green/chimes.html"><span 	class="book">The Chimes</span></a> (1912)</li></ul>                <h3>Bibliography</h3><p class="bibl">Dickens, Charles. <span class="book">The Chimes</span>. Introduction byClement Shorter. Illustrated by Charles Green. The Pears' Centenary Edition. London: A &F Pears, [?1912].</p><p class="bibl">_____. <span class="book">The Chimes: A Goblin Story of Some Bells That Rang An Old Year Out and a New Year In</span>. Illustrated by John Leech, Richard Doyle, Clarkson Stanfield, and Daniel Maclise. London: Bradbury and Evans, 1844 [Printed title-page dated "1845."].</p><p class="bibl">_____. <span class="book">Christmas Books</span>. Illustrated by​ Fred  Barnard. 22 vols. The Household Edition. London: Chapman and Hall, 1878. Vol. XVIII.</p> <p class="bibl">__________.  <span class="book">The Christmas Books</span>. Illustrated by Harry Furniss. Charles Dickens Library Edition. 18 vols. London: Educational Book Company, 1910, VIII, 79-157.</p><p class="bibl">_____. <span class="book">Christmas Stories</span>. Illustrated by​ E. A.Abbey. The Household Edition. 16 vols. New York: Harper and Brothers, 1876. Vol. V.</p><hr><a href ="../../../index.html"><div class="nav-tile"><br/>Victorian<br/>Web</div></a> <a href =".